SIMPLE: haul
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Haul
<hw>Haul</hw> <pr>(h⟦add⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hauled</conjf> <pr>(h⟦add⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hauling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>halen</ets>,
<ets>halien</ets>, F. <ets>haler</ets>, of German or Scand. origin; akin
to AS. <ets>geholian</ets> to acquire, get, D. <ets>halen</ets> to
fetch, pull, draw, OHG. <ets>hol⟦omac⟧n</ets>, <ets>hal⟦omac⟧n</ets>, G.
<ets>holen</ets>, Dan. <ets>hale</ets> to haul, Sw. <ets>hala</ets>, and
to L. <ets>calare</ets> to call, summon, Gr. <grk>kalei^n</grk> to call.
Cf. <er>Hale</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Claim</er>. <er>Class</er>,
<er>Council</er>, <er>Ecclesiastic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pull
or draw with force; to drag.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some dance, some <qex>haul</qex> the rope.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thither they bent, and <qex>hauled</qex> their ships to land.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Romp-loving miss⟦br⟧
Is <qex>hauled</qex> about in gallantry robust.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To transport by drawing, as with horses or oxen;
<as>as, to <ex>haul</ex> logs to a sawmill</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When I was seven or eight years of age, I began <qex>hauling</qex>
all the wood used in the house and shops.</q> <rj><qau>U. S.
Grant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To haul over the coals</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Coal</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To haul the wind</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to turn the head of the ship nearer to the point
from which the wind blows.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Haul
<hw>Haul</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To
change the direction of a ship by hauling the wind. See under
<er>Haul</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I . . . <qex>hauled</qex> up for it, and found it to be an
island.</q> <rj><qau>Cook.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pull apart, as oxen sometimes do when
yoked.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To haul around</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to shift
to any point of the compass; -- said of the wind.</cd> -- <col><b>To
haul off</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to sail closer to the wind,
in order to get farther away from anything; hence, to withdraw; to draw
back.</cd></cs><-- haul off (b), to get ready (usu. for violent action)
-- used with "and" -- "hauled off and punched him on the nose" -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Haul
<hw>Haul</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A pulling with force; a
violent pull.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A single draught of a net; <as>as, to catch a
hundred fish at a <ex>haul</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is caught, taken, or gained at once, as
by hauling a net.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Transportation by hauling; the distance through
which anything is hauled, as freight in a railroad car; <as>as, a long
<ex>haul</ex> or short <ex>haul</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Rope Making)</fld> <def>A bundle of about four
hundred threads, to be tarred.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haulabout</ent>⟦br⟧
